   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><ref
                           target="people.html#Cunobelinus"><title>Cymbeline</title></ref></hi>].
                        <note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"><title><title><ref
                                    target="people.html#Cunobelinus">Cymbeline</ref></title>; A
                              Historical Play, In Five Acts; By <ref
                                 target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William Shakspeare</ref>.
                              As Performed at the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref> and <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>. Printed
                              Under the Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks
                              by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                           Inchbald</ref></title></hi>, London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees,
                        and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"><title
                              level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays, Which Are
                              Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                                 Lane</ref>, <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent
                                 Garden</ref>, and <ref target="people.html#Haymarket"
                                 >Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers from
                              the Prompt Books. With Biographical and Critical Remarks, by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald.</ref></title></hi>
                        In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. IV. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King
                        Lear</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#Cunobelinus">Cymbeline</ref></title></hi>. <hi
                           rendition="#italics"><title><ref target="people.html#Macbeth"
                                 >Macbeth</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#CaesarJulius">Julius Cæsar</ref></title></hi>.
                           <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref target="people.html#AntoniusMarcus"
                                 >Antony</ref> and <ref
                                 target="people.html#CleopatraVIIQueenofEgypt"
                              >Cleopatra</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst,
                        Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play
                        was likely staged at the Blackfriars or Globe Theatre in 1609 or 1610. Laura
                        DeWitt and Mary A. Waters edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The
                           Criticism Archive</hi>. </note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p><ref target="people.html#MaloneEdmond">Mr. Malone</ref> informs the public, that the
               king from whom this play takes its title, began his reign, according to <ref
                  target="people.html#HolinshedRaphael">Holinshed</ref>, in the nineteenth year of
               the reign of <ref target="people.html#CaesarAugustus">Augustus Cæsar</ref>; and the
               play commences in, or about, the twenty-fourth of <ref
                  target="people.html#Cunobelinus">Cymbeline</ref>'s reign, which was the
               forty-second year of <ref target="people.html#CaesarAugustus">Augustus</ref>, and the
               sixteenth of the Christian era.<note>From <ref target="people.html#MaloneEdmond"
                     >Edmond Malone</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Plays and Poems of
                           <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                        Shakspeare</ref></title></hi>, vol. 8, p. 309.</note>&#8212;<ref
                  target="people.html#Cunobelinus">Cymbeline</ref> is said to have reigned
               thirty-five years, leaving at his death two sons, Guiderius, and Arviragus.<note>Both
                  sons are kings in British legend, though it is doubted that either were real
                  historical figures. In <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                     >Shakespeare</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                           target="people.html#Cunobelinus">Cymbeline</ref></title></hi>, Guiderius
                  is the elder of the two brothers, both of whom were kidnapped by the banished
                  lord, Belarius, as infants.</note></p>

            <p>Notwithstanding an English king and his children furnish some names in this tragedy,
               it is supposed, that its fable is taken from an Italian novel, which the dramatist
               has blended with many incidents, the produce of his own fancy.<note>The work to which
                     <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> refers is the ninth tale
                  of the second day in <ref target="people.html#Boccaccio">Giovanni
                  Boccaccio</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Decameron</title></hi> (c.
                  1353).</note></p>

            <p>Variety of events form the peculiar character of this play; attention is kept awake
               by sudden changes of time, place, and circumstances; but the mind obtains little
               reward for its watchfulness. Among the many amusing things, both seen and heard, at
               the representation of "<title><ref target="people.html#Cunobelinus"
                  >Cymbeline</ref></title>," that part in which the great author is concerned,
               generally makes so <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw><pb n="4"
               />slight an impression upon an audience, that, when the curtain is dropped, they
               immediately discourse upon the splendour of Imogen's<note place="foot">The daughter
                  of <ref target="people.html#Cunobelinus">Cymbeline</ref> by a former queen,
                  disguised later in the play as the page Fidele.</note> bed-chamber, the becoming
               dress she wore as a boy, and the dexterity with which Iachimo<note place="foot">A
                  womanizing Roman lord and an acquaintance of Posthumus, Imogen's husband who was
                  initially an orphan raised alongside her by <ref target="people.html#Cunobelinus"
                     >Cymbeline</ref>. Due to his secret marriage with Imogen, Posthumus is banished
                  to Rome, where Iachimo bets that his seduction can sway Imogen from her fidelity
                  to Posthumus. Deceived by Iachimo's subsequent report of Imogen's infidelity,
                  Posthumus orders Pisanio, his servant, to murder Imogen.</note> crept out, and
               crept into his coffer; without bestowing equal observation upon any of those sorrows
               or joys, which they have just seen exhibited.</p>

            <p>Still the impossibility, that half the events in this play could ever occur, cannot
               be the sole cause of its weak effect. <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                  >Shakspeare</ref>'s scenes are frequently such, as could not take place in real
               life; and yet the sensations which they excite are so forcible, that improbability is
               overpowered by the author's art, and his auditors are made to feel, though they
               cannot believe. </p>

            <p>No such magic presides over the play of "<title><ref target="people.html#Cunobelinus"
                     >Cymbeline</ref></title>," as to transform reason into imagination&#8212;the
               spectator may be pleased, but cannot be impassioned. The only scene which approaches
               the pathetic, is that where Imogen is informed by Pisanio, of her husband's command,
               that she should be murdered;&#8212;and this is a vengeance so unlike the forgiving
               temper of an English courtier, upon similar occasions, that it appears, as if the air
               of Italy had, as she suspects, infected the loving Posthumus with that nation's
               predominant crimes, and no one heart is deeply affected by so extraordinary an
               occurrence. </p>

            <p>The young mountaineers, the brothers of Imogen, are pleasing figures, among the large
               group of personages here collected: but still their forest dresses, more than their
               business in the scene, amuse the spec-<pb n="5"/>tator. Or, if he be moved by any
               concern about them, it is with hatred, at the inhuman boasting of Guiderius, that he
               has&#8212;"cut off one Cloten's head, son to the queen, and sent it down the river,
               to tell his mother,"<note>Act IV, scene ii. Cloten is the son of <ref
                     target="people.html#Cunobelinus">Cymbeline</ref> with his second wife, the
                  present Queen.</note> &amp;c. Whoever Cloten was, or whatever ill he might
               threaten,&#8212;yet, for the author to make this youthful forester lay his foolish
               enemy dead at his feet, and then be facetious over the horrid act, was sinking him
               beneath the common bravo, who is ever portrayed grim and gloomy, as the good sign
               that he is still a man, and has a conscience capable of remorse.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Johnson</ref> concludes his commentaries on
               the tragedy of "<title><ref target="people.html#Cunobelinus">Cymbeline</ref></title>"
               (in which he bestows little praise, except on the soliloquy of Posthumus, when he
               supposes Imogen has been put to death) with this general criticism. <quote>This play
                  has many just sentiments, some natural dialogues, and some pleasing scenes; but
                  they are obtained at the expense of much incongruity. To remark the folly of the
                  fiction, the absurdity of the conduct, the confusion of the names, and manners of
                  different times, and the impossibility of the events, in any system of life, were
                  to waste criticism upon unresisting imbecility, upon faults too evident for
                  detection, and too gross for aggravation.<note>From <hi rendition="#italics"
                           ><title>The Plays of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                              Shakespeare</ref>, With the Corrections and Illustrations of Various
                           Commentators</title></hi> (1765), vol. 7, p. 403.</note></quote></p>

            <p>How would a modern author writhe under a critique that should accuse his drama, of
               only one half of these failings!&#8212;Yet "<title><ref
                     target="people.html#Cunobelinus">Cymbeline</ref></title>" survives this just
               attack&#8212;and will live admired, and esteemed, to the end of time.</p>
            <fw type="sig">
               <hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi>
            </fw>
         </div>
      </body>
